<dl id="n08184h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08184h">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08184h"> 184(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <font color="green">[mother]</font> shakes with fright</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In 697 he achieved a great reform. Both women and clergy were still liable to be called out on expeditions of war. The Irish legend tells how Adamnan&apos;s mother, travelling with her son, saw a fight, and a woman on one side having a hook on a pole and the hook fixed in the breast of a woman on the opposite battalion; and Adamnan&apos;s mother sat down and swore she would never move till her son had promised he would &ldquo;free the women of Ireland from hostings and slaughter.&rdquo; <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 38</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
